This is Jane.

Jane's face matches my heart right now—I am reading a novel a friend recommended and it is well written...but so unpleasant and uncomfortable that I have not only lost the will to read but also to live. WHAT IS JOY? I have forgotten.

This is the power of fiction.

(No, I'm not telling you the name of the book, one man's trash is another man's treasure, etc etc)

How maddening that—despite (because?) years of study—there is still a terrible writer in me longing to be freed. Every work day starts with me putting a pillow over her head, and the work day's over when she wrestles it off.

Today I'm actually working on the next room over, in front of a fireplace. As I do, I'm thinking of a piece of wisdom I'd give young writer Maggie if I could: remember that many writing sins are simply the result of the writer lying to themselves about what they still don't know about their book. They don't know what is on the other side of the door, so they don't describe the setting. They don't know what the bad guy is doing right at that moment, so they can't tease it. They don't know what happened in the main character's childhood to make them want what they are chasing, so the writer can't describe a childhood flashback to add context. If you get stuck, young Maggie, ask yourself to be honest about what you don't yet know about your book, and make some decisions.

Also: I need novel recommendations, but I'm going to put a limit on them. They have to have been originally published between 1985-2005, and they have to be standalone novels (and no, I don't mean series books that CAN stand alone), and you have to love them. What do you have for me?

ETA: I made a spreadsheet with all the recs that were inside the parameters, that link's in my bio. 

I set these parameters in order to find books that might have had their biggest moment before the internet became the internet/ Goodreads made it easy to publicly track reads, and to highlight my favorites: standalones—or books that were conceived as standalones, at least, until subsequent installments arrived later. Standalone novels have a different feel to serial fiction, and that was what I was looking for here. I'm going to make this the backbone of my '23 reading list. Titles with asterisks are ones I've already taken a crack at. Thanks for your contributions!

IG makes it pretty tough for me to see individual new comments when I have a lot of activity, so I doubt I'll be very good about updating it with books from new comments, but I'll probably add a few more here and there!

This summer, I'm returning to two locations in the Scottish Highlands to work with nearly 50 writers! Last year was my 1st time attempting small format retreats with students, and I wasn't sure what to expect—tensions can run high when you're locked in a castle with strangers... but it was marvelous. An exhausting, productive time that felt really useful and memorable. 

Because the retreats were so time-consuming, I swore I wasn't going to do it again, but here I am, returning in July. It's beginning to have the feel of an annual tradition. 

The July retreats are already filled with returning students and a handful of newcomers who juried in, but if you'd like to be on the newsletter list for next year's, you can sign up at the link in the bio.

I recently read this battered, strange book—a 1955 memoir by a German soldier who escaped from an American POW camp...and founded a bookstore in Chicago under an assumed name until his capture years later. 

I was reminded of this book today because I was told Shiver was among many books just removed from Clay Co. libraries in Florida (other titles removed include BAN THIS BOOK, by Alan Gratz). A single man nominated them for removal and assessment. 

Pabel, the author of this memoir, was sent by the Nazis to "liberate" Ukraine on the Eastern Front, finding out how false the hero narrative was many months into the war. He spoke both Russian and German, and as a bibliophile, he visited libraries even in the countries he marched through. He wrote at length about the different ways both Germany and Russia censored books-sometimes by altering content, sometimes by simply limiting access. He also writes of how shocked he is to find Americans able to say and read anything they like, speaking against atrocities. Eventually, he became an American.

It's a hard, graphic memoir of war, but it really drove home how censorship and book banning, no matter what you call it, is not about a particular political party: it is simply about consolidating power. 

My kids are now about to turn 18 & 19 and both will tell you that I was a strict parent. But I never felt threatened by the contents of my school library, because I talked with my kids, read what they read, made sure the door was open for them to be curious and critical. 

This openness is what made us a brilliant place to live; I sincerely hope we don't let fear shrink our world to a place we don't recognize.

(Note: please let me know if anything about the Florida situation changes or is incorrect and I'll alter; I'm passing along what was told to me).

One of the highlights of our trip to Amsterdam was the @micropia_amsterdam museum, a museum dedicated to the microscopic. I enjoyed it hugely even though I was in my peak sticky-greasy-jet-lagged form at that point in the trip. They had this kissing exhibit, which was very tricky and hidden—you didn't realize what it was until you stepped in.

The first time I found it, I was with my brother. I opted to not test the meter with him. Instead I lay in wait while he fetched Lover, who had no idea what trap awaited.

Every Sunday, I try to spend a few hours in the studio practicing something—a recording technique, a playing technique, a composing technique. Like my novel-writing and art-making, most of my practice is only for me . . . all that work should be invisible in any final project.

All that invisible work gets saved in notebooks or sketchbooks or on hard drives that will never be released. There’s an example of one of my Sunday sketches in the link in my bio.

I don't much care what these practices tunes, sketches, stories end up sounding or looking like, because they aren't for entertaining other people; they're for teaching me.
To reward myself for finally kicking both a cold and jet lag, I started a new art piece.

This year, I'm focused more than ever on prioritizing my writing. Not putting my writing first, but rather, prioritizing what I ask the reader to look at and remember on each page. Priority. Organization.

Organization is the difference between a story and a novel.

It isn't enough to know everything about your characters, story, plot. In fact, sometimes knowing too much can get in your way. Because readers don't need to know everything: they need to know just enough to create an emotional and intellectual engagement.

An unprioritized novel never builds to something unputdownable. It is just a series of facts and events the reader must remember. It's just work.

It is up to the writer to aggressively prioritize, organize, and stylize those events to make them into something that feels effortless and purposeful.

I think that's more important than ever.

Our modern story tastes are changing faster than ever (it's hard to remember, sometimes, that the novel, as a storytelling form, is very young), and increasingly we're pivoting to highly stylized stories, highly prioritized stories, highly organized stories.

We want to feel the hand of the writer. We want to know the writer is in control, that our time with the page will be worthwhile. Priorities! Not just And then this happened and then this happened and then this happened. 

Instead:

Blue Sargent had forgotten how many times she had been told that she would kill her true love . . . and puzzle the boys' stories inside hers, so we understand that her beginning, middle, and end will dictate where we are in the overall story.

SHIVER is having quite a time this year, getting banned left and right after living quite peacefully on library shelves for over a decade. Of all the novels I've written, I never expected SHIVER to be the one raising eyebrows. Some counties really do not want their kids learning how to be werewolves or reading German poetry.

The Columbia-Marion County Public Library is the latest to pull books from its young adult shelves at parental requests. Support your librarians—they are doing their best in an increasingly unfriendly environment. A small vocal minority shouldn't be allowed to bully their way through our shelves, particularly with dubious tactics: often these lists will include one bonkers off the wall adult book that is clearly full of material not intended for young adults, and protestors will use that as a Trojan horse to push through wider bans of titles they find too progressive, knowing that most people won't ever double check the contents of the rest of the list.

When I was a younger writer, I used to just pour words into a document, and however they turned out, well...that was how they turned out. It was a glorious, id-fueled process that was more about pleasing me as a reader than translating a complicated story for someone else. I vaguely understood that "editing" was meant to happen after the first draft, but I wasn't sure what, exactly, it was supposed to do. Make it better? Better how?

Now, of course, I am a middle aged novelist who has done this dozens of times, and I know that novels are made in editing. Editing is for taking that first keyboard smash of drafting and, first, to get it closer to what you envisioned in your head before you began, and second, to make it as easy as possible for the reader to digest.

It's such an enjoyable and frustrating and weighty part of the work.

I have told this story so many times that I can't believe I just found it was a lie. It goes like this:

Many years ago, I was at a signing, and I was getting a little loopy because it had been a few hours, which might explain why, when someone came through the line and said, "please sign it to Ingrid," I signed it to Diane. I don't know why. There was no Diane there. I knew no Dianes. Anyway, I bought the book from the store so that they wouldn't be stuck with it, and took it home. Quite some time after that, a man came to the house—a repairman, I think? This was Lover's business, not mine—and he mentioned that his wife's name was Diane. Overjoyed, I galloped to get this book for Lover to give it the man, and the story was ended happily.

Or so I thought, because now, a decade later, while moving house, I found this book nestled underneath a decade of model train layout supplies.

I HAVE TOLD THIS STORY SO MANY TIMES AND YET DIANE NEVER GOT THIS BOOK I HAVE BEEN LIVING A LIE

(You can see hold old this story is because the book has my old signature, which I changed a few years into my career because of an entirely different story).

Time for my periodic reminder that aspiring (and established writers) can look for a critique partner at the match-up I established long ago. There are several hundred folks at all experience levels there, link in my bio.

the rules are simple:

STEP ONE: Post a comment saying the age range (adult, YA, MG) of your project, a brief, one-sentence blurb about your book (or just the genre if you don’t want to share more than that), and whether or not you have an agent, etc.*. Also include the last book you read that you loved and also the book you feel epitomizes you as a reader. If you write in a language other than English, include that info with the language in all caps so it’s easy to find while skimming the comments. Finish with a way to contact you.

*You don’t have to include the agent/ publication information unless it’s important to you to find a critique partner who is also agented/ published. I was agented/ published when I met my critique partners; they were not. It depends on the sort of support you’re looking for.

STEP TWO: If someone else in the comments sounds like a possible match, send them a message saying so and find out if it’s mutual. If it is, exchange the first 50 pages of your manuscripts, critique them, and return said critiques. If either of you doesn’t feel like the crit relationship is working at that point, you get to smile and say thanks and walk away without any questions asked. This is VERY IMPORTANT. This ability to shake hands and part ways without hard feelings is the reason why this process works. Sometimes it takes a few exchanges before you realize it’s not a good match. Don’t feel pressured into sticking with each other—remember that this is honest speed dating and a ‘not for me!’ is not a rejection based upon merit.

NOTE: I recommend two or three partners for best results. That way when someone says “this sucks!” and someone else says “does not!” you can be the tie breaker. But if they both say “this sucks!” and you say “does not!” it means you’re wrong.

Five Bookish Gifts for Readers In Your Life, According to Me

In theory, feels as if it should be easy to shop for readers: GET THEM BOOKS. But in practice, readers are proactive (they have already bought what they want to read) and readers are picky (they do not want the books you buy for them). At best, you get them what they already have, and at worst, they regard your bookish choices for them as a personal attack on their very personality. Did you really think they were the sort of human who would like THAT sort of book!?

So, one reader to another, here's five suggestions for what to give the reader in your life.

1. LUMIO book lamp. My agent gave me one of these years ago, and I was sure it would be a fancy dust collector. But it's MAGIC.

2. Book ends. Not the ones that take up more space, no—readers never have enough room as it is! Rather, some sleek, efficient book ends that will allow the reader in your life to turn any available flat space (fridge, window sill, your desk) into a shelf for brimming titles. Pictured are some slick ones from the Container Store.

3. A Reading Journal. Yes, there is Goodreads for keeping track of your reads, but the only drama your reader will find in their journal is what they pen themselves. (shown from Papier)

4. The Arrival, by Shaun Tan. I've been recommending this wordless book for years—I think it's one of the most splendid metaphors for immigration/ integrating into a new culture that's ever been penned. If your reader already has it, not only do they have great taste, but they can easily find another human to gift it to, as EVERYONE SHOULD READ IT AND ENJOY IT.

5. Bookish merch. Nothing says I KNOW WHAT YOU READ LAST SUMMER than scoring the reader in your life some merch based on it. Shown is some swag from collegebookcore on Etsy.

And never forget the best gift you can give a reader, one that costs absolutely nothing: never, ever telling them that you hated a book they recommended.

2023 wasn't a great reading year for me, my friends. I picked up a lot of books; I hurled a lot of books. Some of it was that it was a year of scheduling and emotional turmoil (any year that starts with a family cancer diagnosis and ends with moving is going to be fraught), and some of it was that I feel like I have fallen out of love with my usual genres, or they've fallen out of love with me.

But here are three that managed to keep me to the end this year, quite a feat. 

I did do a ton of nonfiction reading this year for my current novel, but it's all quite spoilery, so I will only admit to reading it after the project's announced this year.

What were your guys' top 3 reads? Were you grinches of reading, like me?
